Entered observation @ 1935. Mother stated to this nurse @ 1950, that daughter felt "light-headed". Water was given. @ 1954, patient started to gag. Went to restroom. @ 1958, she was walked with this nurse and others to "bed" that's located in vaccination clinic. Mother explained to this nurse and others that her daughter shows s/s of these symptoms upon each vaccination. Lightheadedness and nausea lasted for about 10-15 minutes. Cold compress was applied to help relieve s/s from vaccine. States she felt better around 2005. Left observation @ 2005, showed no s/s of distress.

Approximately 20 hours after vaccination patient felt faint, lost all color and fainted. She was in and out of responsiveness. Patient was transported to the ER. Patient was treated with fluids and discharged after observation. According to patient's mom the EKG and lab work were unremarkable. Patient has fully recovered.
16 2021-02-16 dizziness 1917 patient reported dizziness, tightness in chest , hyperventilating and pulse rate of 118 bpm.
16 2021-02-18 dizziness Went to sit down and passed out; felt dizzy; nausious/nausia; sweaty; sick feeling; as she was ghost... Read more
Close
Went to sit down and passed out; felt dizzy; nausious/nausia; sweaty; sick feeling; as she was ghost white; bad headache.; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other Health Professional reported for herself. A 16-year-old female patient received the second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EN5318) via intramuscular on left arm on 02Feb2021 03:45 PM, at age of 16 years old at single dose for Covid-19 immunization. Patient was not pregnant at the time of vaccination. Medical history reported as allergies to medications, food, or other products was reported as none known. Prior to vaccination, patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Other medications the patient received within 2 weeks of vaccination included multivitamin and melatonin gummies. The patient previously received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EL3248), via intramuscular at left arm on 12Jan2021 03:45 PM for Covid-19 immunization. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. It was reported morning after vaccine 03Feb2021 08:00 patient was felt dizzy and nausious. Told her mom and her mom ran over as she was ghost white. Went to sit down and passed out. Patient experienced sweaty, nausia, sick feeling and bad headache. Patient went to the emergency room (ER), they gave fluids and blood work. No heart issues noted. Felt better around 3 hours after. Headache was bad and continued on 05Feb2021 (reported today). Also, still feel nausious and had to lay down. All events occurred on 03Feb2021 08:00 AM. Patient was recovering. It was reported the adverse event result in emergency room/department or urgent care. The seriousness criteria were reported as not serious, no results in death, no life threatening, no caused/prolonged hospitalization, no disabling/incapacitating, no congenital anomaly/birth defect. Patient was received treatment for the adverse event included fluids and heart monitoring. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included blood work in Feb2021. Since the vaccination, patient had not been tested for COVID-19. Outcome of events bad headache and nauseous was not recovered, for felt dizzy, as she was ghost white, passed out, sweaty, sick feeling was recovering.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information provided and plausible temporal association, a contributory of the suspect drug to the reported events cannot be completely excluded. Case will be reassessed when additional information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer drug is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

"Pfizer-Bio-Tech COVID-19 Vaccine EUA" : Individual received the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine. She began to feel dizzy and flushed at 1:00 pm. Her vitals were 82/46, 22, 68, 98% RA at1:00 pm. We applied ice to back of neck. B/P 72/42,20, 76 P, 98 % RA. 1:20 pm. Individual report that he had not drink any fluids and only had a few bites to eat. Patient swallowing intact. She was given bottle of water. 1:46 pm vitals were 82/54, 100% SATS, 81, 14. Individual stated she felt better and was not longer dizzy. 1:55 pm vitals 79/54. 14, 78, 98% RA. Close
Patient was sitting in the observation area. Patient stated that she was feeling "off" and we helped lower her to the ground into a sitting position. She stated that she felt dizzy and we lowered her onto her back and raised her legs onto a chair. 911 was contacted. Patient remained responsive and was able to answer questions throughout. Patient stated that her shoulder felt like it was burning where she received the injection. She also stated that her face felt numb and her lips felt funny (tingling). Patient was still able to breathe and respond appropriately to all questions. Care was taken over by Ambulance service. After speaking with patients mother later in the day, it was determined patient had a vasovagal episode.

16 2021-04-05 dizziness Patient is a 16yo seen for her first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. She was seated in the back seat o... Read more
Close
Patient is a 16yo seen for her first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. She was seated in the back seat of the car. Shortly after receiving her vaccine (within a few minutes), she chose to move to the front passenger seat of the car, and after sitting in the passenger seat she became lightheaded and lost consciousness. Syncopal event was witnessed and lasted a few seconds. She spontaneously regained consciousness, and complained of some lightheadedness and tunnel vision. No significant confusion was noted, her responses to questions were appropriate. Initial pulse was thready and heart rate initially difficult to auscultate. Pale color noted on the face. Initial pulse approximately 50bpm. Breath sounds clear with good air exchange. Patient was placed in a reclined position with feet on the dash. She quickly recovered and repeat heart rate was auscultated at approximately 70bpm, stronger pulse noted. She was noted to have improvement and she was then driven out of the vaccine site after obtaining consent from her mother (who was the driver) and parked beside EMS. BP was 100/50 and HR 68-72, SaO2 97%. Lightheadedness resolved and she was feeling well, at her baseline. She was monitored for 30 min then allowed to leave with her mother, she was at her baseline at last evaluation. Per history review with her mother, she has had 2 prior episodes of syncope with pin removal from hand after surgery and IV placement.

Kept her home from school and she slept a lot. Only vomited the one time. She was fine by late afternoon and all symptoms seemed to have resolved by then.

16 2021-04-08 fall Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attend... Read more
Close
Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attendance after consent was acquired. At 1805 patient began to feel hot and nauseous. The patient thought she was going to vomit, so she left her chair in the waiting area to head to the restroom at the back of the store. at 1807, Upon rising the patient became weak in the knees and began to collapse. The patient's mother initially supported the patient and I was called to assist the patient to the floor. The patient was very pale in appearance as she was assisted gently to the floor, avoiding any injury. EMS was called shortly after the event around 1810. The patient remained conscious however was a bit disoriented initially while lying on the floor. The patient recovered quickly, however remained nauseous and complained of feeling hot. Upon questioning the patient, she had not eaten since lunch at school at 1300. The patient was given a cold water and a sprite, of which she had a couple of drinks out of each. The patient was relocated back into a chair at 1815 as she was feeling much better. EMS arrived at 1821. EMS performed a general assessment and a blood pressure check resulting in 130/80. The patient's mother dismissed any further treatment from EMS. EMS exited the building at 1827. The patient and mother waited in the store for a while longer. Both patient and mother exited on their own, denying escort from associates at 1840.

Close
Acute Infarct of R internal capsule and R basal ganglia; Acute Infarct of R internal capsule and R basal ganglia; Left (L) sided motor deficits; L facial droop; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician. A 16-year-old female patient received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection), dose 1 intramuscular, administered in left arm on 24Mar2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included truncus arteriosus (status post (s/p) right ventricle-to-pulmonary artery (RV-PA) conduit and prosthetic aortic valve s/p automatic implantable cardioverter defibrillator (AICD) placement) and arrhythmias. The patient have no known allergies to medications, food, or other products. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination. The patient was not pregnant at the time of vaccination. Concomitant medications included sotalol taken for arrhythmias and warfarin. The patient was therapeutic on warfarin (INR 2.68) at admission and has been historically very compliant with medication. On 29Mar2021 14:00, the patient experienced acute infarct of right (R) internal capsule and R basal ganglia as diagnosed (dx) on magnetic resonance imagine (MRI), concerning for (C/f) cardio-embolic etiology in the setting of patient's complex cardiac history. However, cannot rule out other causes of infarct. Left (L) sided motor deficits on exam, L facial droop. Transthoracic echocardiogram (TTE) was unchanged from prior. The patient was hospitalized for the events from 29Mar2021 to 05Apr2021. The patient underwent other lab tests and procedures which included COVID-19 nasal swab test was negative on 29Mar2021 and on 30Mar2021. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the events and included treatment with anticoagulation. Outcome of the events was recovered with sequel on 2021. The following information on the batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: As there is limited information in the case provided, the causal association between the events and the suspect vaccine BNT162B2 cannot be excluded. Consider also possible contributory effects from patient's pre-existing cardiac history. The case will be reassessed once new information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer drug is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Patient presented to the ED with dizziness, fever and heavy vaginal bleeding around 24 hours after receiving her first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine. She was tested for active COVID-29 infection via nasal swab PCR and tested positive. Upon presentation labs were drawn and her platelet count was found to be 8 on 5/15. Repeat labs were drawn that day to confirm low platelet count and confirmed diagnosis and thrombocytopenia secondary to an immune reaction to the vaccine was suspected. She was admitted and was started on tranexamic acid, medroxyprogesterone, dexamethasone and IV immunoglobulin (Ig) to help treat low platelet count and vaginal bleeding. As of writing, she is still admitted and her most recent platelet count on 5/17 was 16.

A 16-years-old female patient received the second dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), vaccinated at the age of 16 years old, via an unspecified route of administration, administered in Deltoid Left on 05May2021 15:00 (Batch/Lot Number: ER8735; Expiration Date: 31Jul2021) as single dose for covid-19 immunisation. Patient received the first dose on unknown date. Her daughter had no reaction from the first one that was three weeks prior. The patient medical history included Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. Concomitant medications included lisdexamfetamine mesilate (VYVANSE) taken for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, start and stop date were not reported. Last Wednesday, at 3 pm, caller's daughter received the second vaccine. Her daughter had no ill effects. Her daughter got up the next morning, 18 hours after administration, and passed out. Caller states that they called the squad and her daughter's BP was 70/44. They pushed an IV, transported her daughter, and they were in the ER for 10 hours. The local hospital gave her daughter 2 1/2 bags of fluid and transported her daughter to Hospital. Caller adds that there were 4 liters of fluid given, and her daughter could not sit or stand without her blood pressure dropping for about 8 hours after the incident. There were 2 transports and 2 ER's. Caller asks why were they not told that this is a symptom. She was grateful that she could catch her daughter before she hit her head, but what about parents who leave their kids alone. Last Wednesday, caller's daughter received the vaccine 05May2021 at 3 pm and passed out 06May2021 in the morning. It was the only time she passed out and caller states she saw her daughter's head drop and then was trying and caught her. She was trying to talk to her and her eyes were in the back of her head, and was trying to arouse her. She was out for over a minute. She went to Emergency Room in. They were there for 6 hours. Then, when she could not sit up and her blood pressure was dropping, they recommended Hospital. She was there, this all took place, on Thursday from 9 am or around 8:50 am when she passed out and then they were discharged after 9 pm. It was a 12 hour situation where they were transported and she spent 12 hours in 2 emergency rooms. The only one she had at time was vyvanse but she did not take this before passing out. The last time that she took this would have been nine hours before administration of the vaccine on 05May2021. She did not take it on 06May2021 when the incident happened. She was just getting up. She had only been on this for about a week. It is a stimulant drug but it is out of the system in the evening so people can sleep. She asked each doctors if this had any role in it and they said no. They told her to take it again which they have not started back yet. She has no other medical conditions. Investigations: caller does not provide dates or specific test results. The first ER did bloodwork, urine, chest x-ray. They wanted a CAT scan of her head but caller declined because she thought it was unnecessary. They did an EKG at first in the ER. Nothing was abnormal. She did have some things out of range in bloodwork which is not surprising because she was taking in fluids. Her calcium was low. Nothing was way out of range, nothing was abnormal. The second ER did a follow up EKG but no other tests or bloodwork. According to three physicians, the EKG was fine. A cardiologist reviewed the 2nd EKG and she got a phone call that they wanted her to follow up because of potential abnormal T waves which could have been a result of that much fluid intake and electrolytes being out of sync after that much fluid. They are following up on this. Her father has as vasovagal response hat he has experienced 4-5 times in his lifetime. He has never passed out following a vaccine. Caller had no idea that was even a response to vaccine. He has passed out after giving blood, with severe pain, coming out of anesthetic, and with severe stress. He has never had an extended period of time where his blood pressure was low. She, they could not get, her blood pressure up with fluid after fluid which is why she was transported to the second ER because they thought they did not know what was going on there. Caller states does she think that there may be some relationship and her daughter has this tendency to vasovagal - yes. Was it brought on by the vaccine? Yes. She has never fainted in her life. Caller adds she can see how some many say this may not be related to the vaccine but 18 hours after administration, they can not get her blood pressure up and were in the ER for 12 hours. Treatment included all the fluid, and 2 capsules of acetaminophen. No other treatment. Outcome of events was unknown. Information on Lot/Batch number was available. Patient admitted with myocarditis s/p dose #2 of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine. At the time of the report, she is still hospitalized. From EHR note: Patient was in her usual state of health when she received her second dose of the Pfizer mRNA Covid vaccine on 6/3. She experienced mild myalgias in the day following the vaccine. However, on 6/5 she developed new severe substernal chest pain, dizziness, and dyspnea. Pain radiated to her throat. Given severity of pain, she presented to the emergency department. In the ED she was afebrile, tachycardic, and initially hypertensive. Labs demonstrated WBC 10.9 (N 49, L 27), Hb 11.7, PLT 315. ESR 25, CRP 7.61. Troponin T was mildly elevated at 0.08, consistent with mild cardiac inflammation. SARS-CoV-2 PCR and antibody testing were negative. An EKG was normal. However, an echo demonstrated low-normal LVEF (55%). Otherwise, patient denies nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, cough, runny nose, conjunctivitis, new rashes, arthralgias. Patient was admitted to the cardiology service for further monitoring. Following admission, she was started on ibuprofen. She notes that her substernal chest pain has improved somewhat since admission. Differential for patient's presentation includes infectious, post-infectious, and non-infectious causes of myocarditis. Although post-vaccination mild myocarditis seems likely, we agree with the infectious workup already undertaken, and recommend additional EBV and CMV PCR testing.

Not sleeping well at night due to pressure feeling in her chest up; Not sleeping well at night due to pressure feeling in her chest up; shivers; jaw got paralyzed; she got shaky; feeling bad/ brain fog; burning sensation in her body; She couldn't talk; slight elevated temp (99.7F max); She has been off balance this week since getting her vaccine; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician. A 17-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration on 12Apr2021 (batch/lot number was not reported) as a single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included irritable bowel syndrome, panic attacks, migraines and acne. The patient was not pregnant at the time of vaccination. It was unknown if there were other vaccines in four weeks. The patient did not have Covid prior to vaccination and was not Covid tested post vaccination. Concomitant medications in two weeks included ondansetron hydrochloride (ZOFRAN) taken for anti-nausea, start and stop date were not reported; doxycycline taken for acne, start and stop date were not reported. The patient previously took glycerol (GLYCERIN) and experienced allergies. The patient got her vaccine on 12Apr2021. Two nights after her vaccine (14Apr2021), she got shaky and feeling bad and burning sensation in her body. No fever at that time, but slight elevated temp (99.7F max) the day after the vaccine (13Apr2021). Mother gave her anti-nausea medication (ondansetron hydrochloride 2 mg) and within 5 minutes her jaw got paralyzed. She couldn't talk. It lasted about 30 min. Mother called ambulance and patient was brought to ER. ER didn't do bloodwork or any evaluation. ER didn't know what happened per mother. She has been off balance this week since getting her vaccine (Apr2021). She feels better this morning but she still feels off balance. Not sleeping well at night due to pressure feeling in her chest up and she shivers to get the feeling away per patient (unspecified date). Slept better last night as of 17Apr2021. No facial drooping. She can smile and lift her eyebrows. Patient had "brain fog" this week as well after the vaccine. The adverse events "she got shaky", "feeling bad", "burning sensation in her body", "jaw got paralyzed" and "she couldn't talk" resulted in doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit and emergency room/department or urgent care visit. There was no treatment received for the adverse events. The outcome was recovered on an unspecified date for the events "jaw got paralyzed" and "she couldn't talk"; recovering for the event "not sleeping well at night"; not recovered for the event "off balance"; and unknown for the rest of the events. Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based from temporal relation of event and vaccine administration, Trismus as an event in relation to suspected drug BNT162B2 cannot be totally excluded. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate

Within a couple of minutes of receiving the shot, my daughter felt hotness running down the length of her vaccinated arm and into her hand. Started feeling hot and started to produce a small patch of hives on the outside of the throat and chest. Did vigorous windmill motions with vaccinated arm. She had a feeling of slight unwellness that was followed by a rush of energy. As we leave the store and start to drive home her hives are a little bit worse and she says she feels a little lightheaded and has some heart palpations. But is still reporting a rush of energy. By the time we get home 10 minutes later hives, lightheadedness, and heart palpations have resolved. She feels great the rest of the day. Next day slight redness around the injection site and arm a bit sore. The following day redness is gone but a slight rash is starting to show up around the neck. 5 days later, the rash becomes inflamed, sore, hot and itchy, hives are full upper-body flareups. She takes Allegra 24 for hives control. Rash comes and goes daily. Acts more like hives. Allegra 24 controls hives mostly along with icing. After a few days, the effectiveness of the Allegra 24 is not as efficient with the neck rash. Switches to Zyrtec 24 which seems to provide better relief from both hives and rash around the neck. Sees Dr. April 29th. He advises not to take a second dose of Pfizer at this time and prescribes her an EpiPen.

Client was given a bottle of water and instructed to remain in a semi-fowler's (45 degree) position until vitals stabilized. Patient remained on vaccination site for 30 minutes following the episode of fainting. EMT obtained orthostatic vital signs (vital trend from lying down, to sitting, to standing). Patient was negative for orthostatic hypotension. Symptoms resolved as indicated above in vital signs. Patient stated she was "feeling better" and declined EMS transport. Patient and father were educated by RN on home care (rest and fluids) and to seek emergency medical attention if symptoms persisted or worsened. Patient left the vaccination site at 10:45 with father and sister with steady gait and in no change in status.

Close
Approximately 5 minutes after vaccine administered, patient started feeling nauseous and dizzy. She was also pale and clammy. Offered patient water and allowed to remove face mask. Instructed on breathing slowly in through the nose and out through the mouth. This helped briefly but then patient verbalized that she was feeling more light headed and thought she should lie down on exam table. Remained at patient's side but did not allow her to stand up in order to relocate from chair to exam table. Approximately 7 minutes after vaccine administration, patient briefly lost consciousness for less than 30 seconds and had slight jerking movements during this time. Remained at patient's side and prevented her from falling out of chair, hitting head, or other injury during syncopal event. After patient regained consciousness, she began sipping on water. A cold, wet paper towel was placed to the back of her neck. Continued to observe patient in exam room for another 5 minutes then she was escorted to waiting area by provider. Waiting area was just outside exam room and patient remained in the presence of a patient care technician, as well as her mother. Patient remained in waiting area for a total observation time of 30 minutes. No other adverse events occurred. Patient and mother both reported that patient does not do well after vaccines and has had similar symptoms after other vaccines in the past.

Patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. Patient had previously received first dose of BNT162B2 on an unknown date for COVID-19 immunisation and had no reaction. On 17Jun2021, patient experienced passed out (head flew back)/ her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds and then they called EMS and had HA/ headache, nausea, dizziness and elevated BP. About 10 minutes after the injection, patient started complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness. She got to the point where she had appeared to pass out when she was sitting. The observation nurse was with her when she had complained of the headache, nausea and being dizzy and then her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds. After that 10 seconds she was responsive again but she was still complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness until the EMS arrived. Reporter stated that they have been administering this particular lot number at that location for about 2 weeks now without any incidents until today all of a sudden. 2 of the patient's reactions were kind of typical reactions that they have seen in the past. No further details provided about reactions in the past. The other one (reported in report 1 of 3) that had to be treated with an epinephrine (EPIPEN) was a pretty significant reaction and they have never had multiple reactions back to back like this. Reporter seriousness for events, her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds and then they called EMS, complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness were reported as not serious. Verbatim event relatedness: COVID vaccine: her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds, complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness were unrelated. Seriousness: She would even call it a mild to moderate reaction. She thinks that she would of been fine without medical intervention. She was okay during the time in observation without actual medical intervention other than helping to calm her down and that type of thing. Causality: She doesn't think the COVID vaccine caused the reaction necessarily. She thinks it may of been anxiety induced symptoms. The outcome for events headache was unknown and for other events was recovering. Information on Lot/Batch number was available. Additional information has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on known drug safety profile and temporal relationship, there is reasonable possibility of causal association between the event Loss of consciousness, Headache, nausea, Dizziness, Elevated BP and the suspect drug BNT162B2. Then I start to shake and my heart rate goes way up. Usually I start to cough then vomit and my airway closes. Thankfully this time we were able to slow the process and I never experienced some of the last symptoms.

Close
4/4: Woke up Easter Sunday with the following symptoms: sweats, chills, uncontrollable shaking, fatigue, dizziness, nausea, and shortness of breath. Went to Urgent Care, but it was closed for the holiday, so instead went to ER. See Item 19 for details. I was discharged within an hour because there was nothing seriously wrong with me, doctor wrote it off as a stomach bug and ordered me to rest and hydrate. 4/4 - 4/10: Virtually every day for this week went the exact same. I would wake up between 6-7am, feel nauseous, weak, no appetite, and shaking. Walking around my apartment would leave me utterly exhausted. I would nap from 9am-12pm, then again from 2-4pm. Ate very little, drank water and sports drinks when awake. Breathing was still shaky. Occasional diarrhea. 4/10: Although slightly less ill than the previous 6 days, I still felt weak, shaky, and exhausted. I went back to Urgent Care this time, and the doctor examined me. She noted my left ear was very inflamed and suspected an ear infection. She prescribed me a week of amoxycilin and told me to rest and eat bland foods. 4/12: After 2 days on the antibiotics, some of my symptoms cleared. I was no longer shaking or having shortness of breath, and although still tired, I did not sleep for half the day as I had the previous week. My appetite was not fully there yet, and in the mornings of this week I would wake up feeling nauseous for about 2 hours. On this day 4/12 my period also started, which is unusual. It was not due to start until around April 17th. My period is very regular and light due to being on birth control, so I consider this abnormal. The flow was also very heavy. 4/17: Heavy flow of my period slows significantly and is now just a slight pink/brown color. I only need a liner to contain it. This is also my last day of antibiotics, so I buy a probiotic supplement in the hopes that it will help settle my gut. 4/17-present (4/20): The morning nausea and lack of appetite are still present despite being off the antibiotics. Occasional discomfort in abdomen/chest. Unexplained muscle soreness in hips, legs, back, and chest. My bowel movement schedule has also completely changed. Normally I do not experience a bowel movement until late morning, after 10am. But for the past 2 weeks I have been woken up around 5:30am with a sudden urge. At the beginning of my illness it was diarrhea but now it has transitioned to slightly more solid feces. It is not really diarrhea anymore.

A 25-year-old non-pregnant female patient received the first dose bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration on 06Jan2021 at 11:45 at single dose in left arm for covid-19 immunization. There was no medical history. Concomitant medication included valaciclovir hydrochloride (VALTREX), topiramate (TOPAMAX), lamotrigine (LAMICTAL), duloxetine hydrochloride (CYMBALTA), ziprasidone hydrochloride (GEODON). On 06Jan2021 at 12:30, The patient experienced heart rate shot up to 170 with numbness of feet, started to feel chest pain, and feeling like she was going to vomit and faint. The events required emergency room visit and were reported as serious per hospitalization. Heart rate at the hospital was 135-140 where two EKG were done and fluids were given. An x-ray of the heart was done and blood work was completed. The patient didn't receive treatment for the events. The patient didn't receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination, and has not been tested for COVID-19 since the vaccination. The outcome of the events was resolved in Jan2021. Information on batch/lot number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: There is a reasonable possibility that the event "feeling like she was going to vomit" was related to BNT162b2 based on known drug safety profile. Based on the temporal relationship, the association between the other reported serious events with BNT 162b2 can not be completely excluded. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

Patient walked up to the observation desk around 1449, during her 30 minute observation period, with complaints of "dizziness, rapid heart rate, and feeling hot." Patient was conscious, alert, and oriented x4 and claimed symptoms began 2 minutes status post vaccine administration. Patient denied any reaction after receiving the 1st dose of Pfizer vaccine and denied experiencing any chest pain, headache, nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea. EMTs had patient sit in the anti- gravity chair for further evaluation. Nurse responded to EMTs with patient. At 1455, EMT obtained baseline vital signs, while patient was sitting: blood pressure: 124/70, heart rate: 72, respiratory rate: 15. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Skins were warm, dry, and normal. Chief complaint of "dizziness, rapid heart rate, and feeling hot" was reassessed and patient stated that symptoms had subsided. Patient explained that the symptoms had a sudden onset, but lasted less than 1 minute. Patient has a history of migraines and an allergy to Penicillin. Patient stated that she had a similar reaction after receiving a dose of Benadryl, earlier this year. Patient told EMTs that she had eaten toast, tofu, and salad about an hour and a half prior to coming to the vaccination site, with limited fluid intake. EMTs gave the patient a water bottle to sip on. At 1502 a second set of vital signs were obtained by EMT, while the patient was sitting: blood pressure: 116/68, heart rate: 74, respiratory rate: 15. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Patient was advised to stay an additional 30 minutes in observation for continued evaluation. Patient stated she "felt better" and all symptoms had improved. Final set of vital signs were taken at 1514 by EMT, while patient was standing: blood pressure: 114/64, heart rate: 72, respiratory rate: 12. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Skins were warm, dry, and normal. Patient was negative for orthostatic pressures. At 1540, patient stated she "felt normal and that all symptoms were gone." Patient had finished the water bottle provided. Patient was then educated on expected/ adverse reactions, when to follow up with her primary care provider, and the use of V- Safe. Patient ambulated with a steady gait on her own accord out of the facility.

About 5 to 10 minutes after receiving the vaccine, the patient reported feeling unwell, saying she felt like she was about to faint. She reported no chest tightness, shortness of breath, or trouble breathing upon being asked. She drank some water. I (the pharmacist who administered the vaccine) then asked her to lay flat on the floor, which she did. The pharmacy technician called 911, but the patient said she was going to be ok and refused an ambulance. I took her pulse manually, and it was about 59 BPM. After about 5 minutes of lying down, she said she was feeling well enough to get up and sat back up on a chair. She did not lose consciousness at any time. She drank some Gatorade. I took her blood pressure and pulse twice about three minutes apart with an automatic monitor and the readings were 127/78 mmHG, pulse 68BPM and 108/67, pulse 67 BPM, respectively. She remained sitting and drinking Gatorade for about 20 more minutes and then left.
